                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d53">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee (Arms)/188:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        American Delegate</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 30, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>494. Your No. 1029, March 29, 8 p.m. We are still of the opinion expressed in
                    paragraph 3 of Department’s No. 472, February 25, 7 p.m. Nevertheless, we do not
                    feel that you should insist on the maintenance of the provisions of the
                    Convention in time of war if such insistence would place the Delegation in
                    opposition to all or almost all of the other important Delegations. You are,
                    therefore, authorized, in your discretion, if you feel that the situation
                    demands it, to acquiesce in the position which appears to be that of the
                    overwhelming majority.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
